{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"63abbe87-b56d-4f9d-9e50-061b60195fd9","content":"Here's how to collect a CPU trace from a .NET 8 app in a Windows container on K8s:\n\n### 1. Get a shell into the container\n```powershell\nkubectl exec -it <pod-name> -- powershell\n```\n\n### 2. Install `dotnet-trace` (if not already present)\n```powershell\ndotnet tool install --global dotnet-trace\n```\n\n### 3. Find your process ID\n```powershell\ndotnet-trace ps\n```\n\n### 4. Collect the trace\n```powershell\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\nThis writes a `.nettrace` file in the current directory.\n\n### 5. Copy it out of the pod\n```powershell\nkubectl cp <pod-name>:<path-to-file>.nettrace ./trace.nettrace\n```\n\n### 6. Analyze\nOpen the `.nettrace` in **Visual Studio**, **PerfView**, or convert it:\n```powershell\ndotnet-trace convert trace.nettrace --format speedscope\n```\nThen load the `.speedscope.json` at [speedscope.app](https://www.speedscope.app).\n\n> **Tip:** If `dotnet tool install` fails due to network restrictions, you can copy `dotnet-trace` into the container image at build time, or use `kubectl cp` to push the tool in.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"5b8f2ca2-61a8-4079-8028-d3eb7feed5a6","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a performance trace from a .NET 8 application running in a Windows container on Kubernetes. This is a knowledge/advice question, not a code change task. I should provide concise, actionable steps.","outputTokens":413,"requestId":"7644:F41F2:D30C36:F71032:69FE8C60"},"id":"522cb2d0-1e74-457d-a88b-03f428e4a8ec","timestamp":"2026-05-09T01:22:50.446Z","parentId":"2b9d29c3-0d9f-4920-81e7-86c9f3f25cd8"}
